1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,872
You've found a strategy that returns 18% per year. Is

2
00:00:03,972 --> 00:00:08,369
that alpha — genuine skill generating returns above what the

3
00:00:08,469 --> 00:00:12,416
market compensates — or is it just levered exposure to

4
00:00:12,516 --> 00:00:16,988
known risk factors that any investor could replicate cheaply?

5
00:00:17,083 --> 00:00:20,062
Factor models answer this question. And

6
00:00:20,162 --> 00:00:22,983
the answer is almost always humbling.

7
00:00:25,583 --> 00:00:29,024
Welcome to QuantiFire. Factor models are the

8
00:00:29,124 --> 00:00:33,451
fundamental decomposition tool of quantitative finance.

9
00:00:33,550 --> 00:00:38,149
Every return stream can be broken into systematic components

10
00:00:38,249 --> 00:00:43,005
— factors — plus an idiosyncratic residual. Understanding that

11
00:00:43,105 --> 00:00:47,626
decomposition tells you what you're actually being paid for

12
00:00:47,726 --> 00:00:50,994
and whether that compensation is efficient.

13
00:00:53,583 --> 00:00:57,639
Every asset return decomposes into three parts:

14
00:00:57,739 --> 00:01:01,883
alpha, factor exposure, and idiosyncratic noise.

15
00:01:01,983 --> 00:01:05,349
Alpha — shown in gold — is the return you

16
00:01:05,449 --> 00:01:11,267
generated through genuine skill, unexplained by any systematic factor.

17
00:01:11,366 --> 00:01:14,620
Factor exposure — in teal — is your

18
00:01:14,720 --> 00:01:20,178
sensitivity to market-wide forces like momentum, value, or

19
00:01:20,278 --> 00:01:24,778
size, multiplied by how those factors performed.

20
00:01:24,866 --> 00:01:29,935
Idiosyncratic noise — in red — is just randomness that no factor

21
00:01:30,035 --> 00:01:35,346
explains. The key insight: if most of your return comes from factor

22
00:01:35,446 --> 00:01:41,645
exposure, you are not generating alpha. You are harvesting known risk premiums

23
00:01:41,745 --> 00:01:45,118
— and you should be paying much lower fees.

24
00:01:47,716 --> 00:01:52,954
The original model was CAPM — a single factor: the

25
00:01:53,054 --> 00:01:59,574
market. Everything in excess of the market return adjusted for

26
00:01:59,674 --> 00:02:05,872
beta is alpha. Sharpe (1964) and Lintner (1965) showed that

27
00:02:05,972 --> 00:02:14,520
if markets are efficient, beta fully explains cross-sectional return differences.

28
00:02:14,616 --> 00:02:19,008
But empirically, the single-factor model fails. Stocks

29
00:02:19,108 --> 00:02:23,750
with certain characteristics earn consistent returns that

30
00:02:23,850 --> 00:02:26,828
pure market exposure doesn't explain.

31
00:02:26,916 --> 00:02:33,712
Small-cap stocks systematically outperform large-cap. Value stocks outperform growth.

32
00:02:33,812 --> 00:02:38,092
Past winners keep winning. These are returns that beta

33
00:02:38,192 --> 00:02:42,473
alone simply cannot explain — which means CAPM's alpha

34
00:02:42,573 --> 00:02:46,448
is contaminated by these hidden factor exposures.

35
00:02:49,033 --> 00:02:53,970
Fama and French published their 3-Factor Model in 1993 in the

36
00:02:54,070 --> 00:02:59,421
Journal of Financial Economics. It adds two factors to the market.

37
00:02:59,516 --> 00:03:05,035
MKT is the original market factor. SMB — Small Minus Big —

38
00:03:05,135 --> 00:03:12,784
captures the size premium: small-cap stocks earn more than large-cap on average.

39
00:03:12,883 --> 00:03:16,286
HML — High Minus Low — captures the value

40
00:03:16,386 --> 00:03:21,668
premium: value stocks with high book-to-market ratios earn more

41
00:03:21,768 --> 00:03:26,794
than growth stocks. Together these two factors explain about

42
00:03:26,894 --> 00:03:31,407
90% of the cross-sectional variation in stock returns.

43
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:39,948
The single market factor of CAPM was published in 1964.

44
00:03:40,033 --> 00:03:43,833
Fama and French extended it to three factors

45
00:03:43,933 --> 00:03:47,733
in 1993, adding the size and value premiums.

46
00:03:47,833 --> 00:03:52,414
Carhart added a fourth factor in 1997: MOM — momentum

47
00:03:52,514 --> 00:03:57,713
— trailing 12-month return minus the last month. Momentum is

48
00:03:57,813 --> 00:04:03,189
one of the most robust and controversial anomalies in finance.

49
00:04:03,283 --> 00:04:07,760
Fama and French extended to five factors in 2015,

50
00:04:07,860 --> 00:04:12,430
adding RMW — Robust Minus Weak profitability — and

51
00:04:12,530 --> 00:04:18,688
CMA — Conservative Minus Aggressive investment. Together these five

52
00:04:18,788 --> 00:04:23,919
factors explain most of the variation in equity returns.

53
00:04:24,016 --> 00:04:27,920
The Fama-French 5-Factor model is now the standard

54
00:04:28,020 --> 00:04:32,004
baseline for factor attribution in equity research.

55
00:04:36,600 --> 00:04:44,292
Portfolio attribution: decompose your returns into factor exposures. This portfolio

56
00:04:44,392 --> 00:04:49,268
returned 18% — let's see where it actually came from.

57
00:04:50,166 --> 00:04:54,761
If 80% of your alpha is just HML loading — value factor

58
00:04:54,861 --> 00:04:59,713
exposure — you are not an alpha generator. You are a value

59
00:04:59,813 --> 00:05:06,030
investor with leverage. You could replicate that exposure at a fraction of

60
00:05:06,130 --> 00:05:11,579
the cost with a value ETF. This insight, from Tulchinsky et al.'s

61
00:05:11,679 --> 00:05:16,274
Finding Alphas, is what drives the factor ETF industry.

62
00:05:19,866 --> 00:05:23,906
Two portfolios can have identical total volatility

63
00:05:24,006 --> 00:05:28,046
but completely different factor exposure profiles.

64
00:05:28,133 --> 00:05:33,129
Portfolio A has 80% of its risk concentrated in market

65
00:05:33,229 --> 00:05:39,546
beta. Portfolio B diversifies across multiple factors. Both show 15%

66
00:05:39,646 --> 00:05:45,963
volatility — but Portfolio B is genuinely better diversified. Factor

67
00:05:46,063 --> 00:05:51,625
models make this visible. Without them, you're flying blind.

68
00:05:55,216 --> 00:06:00,320
Factor construction in DeFi: on-chain data generates novel factor

69
00:06:00,420 --> 00:06:04,884
signals that map directly onto the Fama-French framework.

70
00:06:04,983 --> 00:06:11,356
TVL Momentum — protocols gaining total value locked outperform — is the

71
00:06:11,456 --> 00:06:17,921
DeFi analogue of the size premium. Revenue Yield — protocol fees divided

72
00:06:18,021 --> 00:06:22,571
by fully diluted value — maps to the value premium.

73
00:06:22,666 --> 00:06:27,499
Holder concentration — a novel on-chain factor with no traditional

74
00:06:27,599 --> 00:06:32,581
analogue — captures distributed ownership as a quality signal. We'll

75
00:06:32,681 --> 00:06:36,990
build these factors from on-chain data in a future episode.

76
00:06:39,583 --> 00:06:43,583
The covariance matrix estimated via factor models is

77
00:06:43,683 --> 00:06:47,211
far more stable than direct sample estimation.

78
00:06:47,300 --> 00:06:52,626
Direct estimation of a 500-asset covariance matrix requires

79
00:06:52,726 --> 00:06:57,408
over 125,000 parameters — highly unstable unless you

80
00:06:57,508 --> 00:07:00,352
have thousands of years of data.

81
00:07:00,450 --> 00:07:05,540
With a 5-factor model, you estimate only 5 loadings per

82
00:07:05,640 --> 00:07:10,919
asset — just 2,500 parameters total. Same 500 assets. Far

83
00:07:11,019 --> 00:07:16,582
more stable. This is the core advantage of factor-based risk

84
00:07:16,682 --> 00:07:22,622
models used by Barra, Axioma, and every major quantitative shop.

85
00:07:24,216 --> 00:07:28,600
Run a factor regression on any strategy before declaring

86
00:07:28,700 --> 00:07:32,924
alpha. Use the Fama-French 5 factors as your baseline.

87
00:07:33,016 --> 00:07:38,488
If your alpha shrinks to near-zero after factor adjustment, your strategy

88
00:07:38,588 --> 00:07:43,677
is factor harvesting — valuable, but very different from true alpha.

89
00:07:43,777 --> 00:07:48,180
Only what survives factor adjustment is worth calling edge.

90
00:07:48,766 --> 00:07:53,884
Next: the Black-Litterman Model — how to inject your own market

91
00:07:53,984 --> 00:07:59,765
views into a portfolio optimizer in a mathematically rigorous way. This

92
00:07:59,865 --> 00:08:03,906
is how the big funds do it. Subscribe. QuantiFire.

